WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:05.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:20.510 --> 00:00:28.810
[ Applause ]

00:00:28.810 --> 00:00:30.110
&gt;&gt; Jane McAuliffe:
Ladies and gentlemen,

00:00:30.110 --> 00:00:32.950
welcome to the library of Congress.

00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:35.590
I have the great honor
and pleasure as head

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:40.620 position:56%
of the Library's new division,
National and International Outreach,

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:45.600
of welcoming you here this evening
for the Living Legend Award.

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:48.200
First of all, I want
to acknowledge members

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:52.370
of the diplomatic community
who are with us tonight.

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:54.920
Among them are a number of
diplomats from countries

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:58.280
that have figured large
in the life and career

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:01.900
of our awardee, Mario Vargas Llosa.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:05.640
Please welcome Ambassador
Luis Miguel Castilla of Peru.

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:06.940
[ Applause ]

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:20.650
I cannot -- Spain's
Ambassador, Ramon Gil-Casares.

00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:27.150
[ Applause ]

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:30.200
The Mexican Ambassador,
Miguel Basanez.

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:36.740
[ Applause ]

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:39.960
Ambassador Martin Lousteau
of Argentina.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:45.840
[ Applause ]

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:49.210
Sweden's Deputy Chief of
Mission, Goran Lithell.

00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:50.510
[ Applause ]

00:01:50.510 --> 00:01:57.490
And the former Ambassador from
the United States to Peru,

00:01:57.490 --> 00:01:59.730
Ambassador Alexander Watson.

00:01:59.730 --> 00:02:04.940
[ Applause ]

00:02:04.940 --> 00:02:09.040
We are delighted to have all of you
join us for this happy occasion.

00:02:09.040 --> 00:02:13.240
I also want to welcome our most
recent Living Legend Awardee,

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:16.360
whose award was conferred
last November.

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:19.100
She is a vibrant force
in the musical world,

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:22.030
the prodigiously talented
Marta Castals Istomin.

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:23.330
[ Applause ]

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:32.730
And last, but certainly not least,

00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:35.380
I would like to recognize
the individual responsible

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:38.640
for this award, the man who
has played a pivotal role

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:42.520
in naming the Living Legends
for the last 16 years,

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:45.820
Librarian of Congress
Emeritus James H. Billington.

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:47.120
[ Applause ]

00:02:47.120 --> 00:03:01.350 position:56%
Thank you also to the
distinguished novelists and scholars

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:06.200
who informed us so richly
about Mario Vargas Llosa's work

00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:08.930
in this afternoon's symposium.

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:12.200
You'll find their names
listed in your program.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:15.350
They've come a long way to
pay homage to this awardee.

00:03:15.350 --> 00:03:24.830
Let's give them a big hand.

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:26.130
[ Applause ]

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:29.610
The Living Legend Award was
inaugurated 16 years ago

00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:34.520
in the year 2000, exactly
200 years after the formation

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:36.890
of the Library of Congress.

00:03:36.890 --> 00:03:41.010
The then-Librarian of Congress,
James Billington, was seeking a way

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:46.240
to mark the Library's bicentennial
by celebrating artists, scholars,

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:49.200
and professionals across
disciplines,

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:54.480
individuals who had made lasting
impressions on American culture.

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:58.730
Their fields might be science,
or literature, or medicine,

00:03:58.730 --> 00:04:03.320
or the media, or politics, or
entertainment, or the fine arts.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.250
It didn't matter, but their
work needed to be trailblazing

00:04:07.250 --> 00:04:12.490
in some way, transformational,
electric, enduring.

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:16.260
And their contributions had
to say something important

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:22.730
about what it means to be American
and what it means for Americans

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:25.060
to be citizens of the world.

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:27.970
This is why we are
gathered here tonight,

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:30.560
to celebrate the many
accomplishments

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:34.140
of a writer who's had
a profound effect

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:37.480
on the American reading
public, the Peruvian novelist

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:41.030
and essayist Mario Vargas Llosa.

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:43.470
Ladies and gentlemen,
without further ado,

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:47.250
we offer a brief history
of this remarkable writer.

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:50.510
Let's roll the video, please.

00:04:50.510 --> 00:04:53.120
[ Music ]

00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:59.350
&gt;&gt; If anything can be said
to define Mario Vargas Llosa,

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:04.270
it is his passion for words, a
passion that leaps exuberantly

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:08.310
from genre to genre, from
spoken to written works.

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:12.730
He is best known for his
fiction, which can be spirited,

00:05:12.730 --> 00:05:15.730
whimsical, or deadly serious.

00:05:15.730 --> 00:05:19.350
His novels are well-known
for exposing human frailties

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:23.260
and plumbing dark chapters
of human history.

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:26.410
But fiction is not his only domain.

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:29.350
He has excelled in
theater, journalism,

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:31.920
literary criticism, opinion.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:35.520
He has given us drama,
memoir, critical essays,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:38.100
social and political commentary,

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:41.760
scholarly argument,
literary scholarship.

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:45.020
And he has done so with
rare intellectual vigor

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:49.320
and a keen appreciation
of the human heart.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:52.390
He learned to read at the age
of five in a Catholic school

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:58.540 position:56%
in Cochabamba, Bolivia, where he and
his mother were living at the time.

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:03.870 position:56%
It was reading, he says, that opened
the door to a life of writing.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:09.870
Jorge Mario Pedro Vargas
Llosa was born on March 28th,

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:17.160 position:56%
1936 in Arequipa, Peru, but he spent
his early childhood years in Bolivia

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:18.890
where he was raised by his mother

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:22.590
and his grandfather,
a Peruvian diplomat.

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:26.550
He moved to Piura,
Peru when he was 10,

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:28.580
and shortly thereafter his parents,

00:06:28.580 --> 00:06:31.550
who had been divorced
before he was born,

00:06:31.550 --> 00:06:35.120 position:56%
were reunited and resettled in Lima.

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:39.860
When Mario was 14, his father
sent him to the military academy

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:44.820
that became the inspiration for
his novel "The Time of the Hero."

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:48.670
It was there, steeped in
the rigors of military life,

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:53.750
that Vargas Llosa developed
the second greatest passion

00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:57.730
of his career, a deep
regard for freedom.

00:06:57.730 --> 00:07:02.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Even as he was being prepared for
a military career he began working

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:08.780 position:56%
for local newspapers, first in Lima
at the age of 16, and then in Piura.

00:07:08.780 --> 00:07:14.320
In 1952 he saw his first play,
"The Flight of the Inca,"

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:17.650
come to life onstage in Piura.

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:21.600
It was the beginning of a lifelong
love affair with storytelling.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:26.400
Convinced that his future was in
words, he decided to study law

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:30.980
and literature at the
University of San Marcos in Lima.

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:34.230
While still a student he
married his first wife,

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:38.000
Julia Urquidi, at the age of 19.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:43.680
Graduating from San Marcos in
1958, he won a scholarship to study

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:48.370 position:56%
at Complutense University in Madrid,
where he received a Doctorate

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:50.790
in Philosophy and Literature.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:54.850
He went on to Paris, hoping to
win another scholarship there.

00:07:54.850 --> 00:07:59.490 position:56%
And when those hopes were dashed,
he began writing stories in earnest.

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:05.180
To make ends meet he worked as a
reporter for Agence France-Presse

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:08.290
and the French National
Television Network.

00:08:08.290 --> 00:08:12.740
It was in Paris, he says, that
he began reading literature

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:15.200 position:56%
from other Latin American countries,

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:18.470
and eventually met the
Chilean poet Pablo Neruda,

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:23.270 position:56%
the Cuban novelist Alejo Carpentier,

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:27.500
and the Argentine writer
Jorge Luis Borges.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:32.200
In Paris, too, Vargas Llosa became
part of the historic flourishing

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.670
of literature now known as
the Latin American Boom.

00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:40.270
A cadre of brilliant young
writers who inspired one another

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:45.760 position:56%
to write the landmark Latin American
masterpieces of the '60s and '70s.

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:52.500
They were Gabriel Garcia Marquez,
Jose Donoso, Jorge Edwards,

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:59.910
Carlos Fuentes, Julio Cortazar,
and of course, Mario Vargas Llosa.

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:04.070
Within a few years they would all
be read in English and translated

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:06.930
into languages around the world.

00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:11.820 position:56%
Vargas Llosa's first published
work, a collection of short stories,

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:15.340
was received favorably,
but it was his first novel,

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:20.950 position:56%
"The Time of the Hero," published in
1963, with it's penetrating portrait

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:24.560
of an entrenched military
establishment in Peru,

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:27.890
that earned him a coveted
prize in Spain,

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:31.470
and an immediate place among the
most celebrated young writers

00:09:31.470 --> 00:09:33.470
of Latin America.

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:37.080
His first marriage
dissolved at about that time,

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:40.280
and he married his
cousin Patricia Llosa,

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:43.480
by whom he would eventually
have three children,

00:09:43.480 --> 00:09:48.160
Alvaro, Gonzalo, and Morgana.

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:52.600
His second novel, "The Green
House," about a legendary brothel

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:55.710 position:56%
for soldiers in the Peruvian jungle,

00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:59.310
won him even more accolades
and readers.

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:03.430
Every book since has been a
departure from the one before,

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:07.960
alternating from humorous,
even erotic flights of fancy,

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:11.100
to pivotal questions of history.

00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:15.370
He has given us in all more than
a dozen unforgettable novels

00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:18.510
and a wide variety of nonfiction.

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:23.880
Among these are "Conversation in
the Cathedral," "Captain Pantoja

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:28.540
and the Special Service," "Aunt
Julia and the Script Writer,"

00:10:28.540 --> 00:10:33.780
"The War at the End of the World,"
"Who Killed Palomino Molero?"

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:37.650
"In Praise of the Stepmother,"
"Death in the Andes,"

00:10:37.650 --> 00:10:42.460
"A Fish in the Water," "The
Notebooks of Don Rigoberto,"

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:46.620
"Letters to a Young Novelist,"
"The Feast of the Goat,"

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:51.750
"The Way to Paradise," "The Bad
Girl," "The Dream of the Celt,"

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:55.890
and most recently,
"The Discreet Hero."

00:10:55.890 --> 00:10:57.520
For this remarkably diverse work

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:04.310
in letters he has been awarded
all the major literary prizes

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:07.710
in Spain and Latin America.

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:09.910
He has been decorated
by France, Mexico, Peru,

00:11:09.910 --> 00:11:11.680
Nicaragua, The Dominican Republic.

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:14.330
He has been accorded a
title of Spanish nobility.

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:16.490 position:56%
He has been awarded the Nobel Prize.

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:21.020
But these contributions are not
confined to the pages of his books.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:23.700
For many decades now this writer

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:28.400
and thinker has been a tireless
participant on the world stage.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:29.770
He has taught at a number

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:34.400 position:56%
of prominent universities throughout
Europe and the United States.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:39.060
He has participated in
theatrical works not only as writer

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:41.590
or director, but as actor.

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:45.120
He had taken an active
part in world commentary,

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:48.520
whether it be about arts,
politics, or culture.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:54.040 position:56%
He has lectured widely about the
relevance of the arts in human life.

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:56.580
&gt;&gt; He has been President
of PEN International.

00:11:56.580 --> 00:12:02.410
He has run a vigorous campaign for
the Presidency of his native land

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:06.560
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa has,
in short, been a passionate,

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:11.420
vibrant force not only in the
realm of the imagination and ideas,

00:12:11.420 --> 00:12:14.520
but in the larger sphere
of human affairs.

00:12:14.520 --> 00:12:21.910 position:56%
If the Library of Congress' Living
Legend Award is meant to honor those

00:12:21.910 --> 00:12:26.550
who have made significant
contributions

00:12:26.550 --> 00:12:34.010 position:56%
to our cultural heritage, then Mario
Vargas Llosa is eminently deserving

00:12:34.010 --> 00:12:35.310
of this prize.

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:36.610
There are few who have done
so much to bring luster

00:12:36.610 --> 00:12:37.910
to Spanish-language
letters and enrich culture

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:39.710
in the 20th and 21st centuries.

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:46.510
[ Music ]

00:12:46.510 --> 00:13:09.390
[ Applause ]

00:13:09.390 --> 00:13:11.780
&gt;&gt; Ladies and gentlemen,
the Ambassador of Peru

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:17.510
to the United States of
America, Luis Miguel Castilla.

00:13:17.510 --> 00:13:26.640
[ Applause ]

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:30.060
&gt;&gt; Luis Miguel Castilla:
I'm truly honored to be part

00:13:30.060 --> 00:13:32.090
of this important celebration.

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:36.310
First of all, I would like to
thank the Library of Congress

00:13:36.310 --> 00:13:40.140
for generally hosting us
this evening on the occasion

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:44.410 position:56%
of bestowing a special
recognition upon Mario Vargas Llosa.

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:47.850
I would also like to acknowledge
a brilliant Peruvian novelist

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:51.200
and journalist, Marie Arana,
who has been instrumental

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:53.400
in putting together
this important event.

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:55.200
Gracias, Marie.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:14:02.290
[ Applause ]

00:14:02.290 --> 00:14:06.530 position:56%
Indeed, this time Mario Vargas
Llosa is being given the prestigious

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:09.770
Living Legend Award,
which the Library

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:14.770
of Congress confers upon prominent
figures whose career have made an

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:19.750
impact in a unique and creative
way in the American community,

00:14:19.750 --> 00:14:24.040
contributing to its development
and its diverse cultural heritage.

00:14:24.040 --> 00:14:27.510
Mario, who received the
Nobel Prize in literature

00:14:27.510 --> 00:14:33.820
in 2010 is making history again,
this time in the United States,

00:14:33.820 --> 00:14:38.100
receiving a distinction previously
conferred to artists, writers,

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:41.340
thinkers, social activists,
politicians,

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:45.750
and even sports figures, thereby
joining his name with that

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:49.280
of the influential economist
John Kenneth Galbraith,

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:53.160
and the no-less-significant
political scientist George Kennan,

00:14:53.160 --> 00:14:56.150
the accomplished photographer
Annie Leibovitz,

00:14:56.150 --> 00:15:00.250
the brilliant guitarist B.B.
King, among many others.

00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:04.680
This is undoubtedly a unique award
honoring distinguished figures

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:07.030
who contributed to the
endeavors of a community

00:15:07.030 --> 00:15:11.340
with deeply-rooted traditions
and values of its own,

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:13.150 position:56%
and upon which it has emerged as one

00:15:13.150 --> 00:15:17.320
of the most influential
living cultures in the world.

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:22.470
I am very proud as a fellow
Peruvian of Mario's accomplishments

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:25.130
which have contributed to
placing very high the name

00:15:25.130 --> 00:15:29.340
of our country not only in the
U.S., but around the world.

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:34.010
In this particular case,
the fact of being in one

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:37.070
of the most important
libraries in the world,

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:41.780
in the heart of Washington, and in
one of the most vibrant democracies

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:44.640
on the planet, demonstrates
importance

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:49.040 position:56%
of Mario's work while
acknowledging his personal qualities

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:53.460
and a lifetime struggle for
democratic values and freedom.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:56.560
Mario Vargas Llosa has proven

00:15:56.560 --> 00:16:00.050
to be a great promoter
of the Peruvian culture.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:03.460
Through Mario's books one
can learn about a complex

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:05.770
and fascinating country like Peru.

00:16:05.770 --> 00:16:09.480
In his books, such as
"La Ciudad y los Perros,"

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:13.930
"Pantaleon y las Visitadoras," and
"La Casa Verde," among many others,

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:18.010
readers discover a mysterious
country with overlapping,

00:16:18.010 --> 00:16:21.810
conflicting, and sometimes
contradictory realities,

00:16:21.810 --> 00:16:25.400
representing exceptional
testimonies of the variety,

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:28.880
wealth, and diversity of Peru.

00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:33.150
On a personal note, as many
Peruvians of my generation,

00:16:33.150 --> 00:16:36.410
I have learned a great
deal from Mario's novels,

00:16:36.410 --> 00:16:41.460
spending hours devouring his books
and learning about our own history,

00:16:41.460 --> 00:16:44.010
its richness and paradoxes.

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:47.210
As him, I grew up in Miraflores.

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:52.160
My father attended the same
Leoncio Prado military school.

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:58.000 position:56%
The first play I ever attended was
"La Senorita de Tacna" 35 years ago.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.540
And the first time I personally
met Mario was almost five years ago

00:17:02.540 --> 00:17:04.640
during a brilliant presentation

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:08.750
at the Cervantes Institute
in New York City.

00:17:08.750 --> 00:17:12.260
In all truth, I have been
captivated throughout my life

00:17:12.260 --> 00:17:15.490
by his story telling and
his skillful capabilities

00:17:15.490 --> 00:17:20.470
of enthralling his readers page
after page, transporting them

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:25.510
from the streets of Santa
Domingo in "La Fiesta del Chivo,"

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:28.030
to Lima's old Barrios Altos quarter

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:31.700
in his most recent
novel "Cinco Esquinas."

00:17:31.700 --> 00:17:35.330
Not only has Mario's
literary work been important,

00:17:35.330 --> 00:17:37.960
but also his outstanding
journalistic work throughout

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:39.260
his life.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:43.360
