00:35:46.480 --> 00:35:50.570
What is really most remarkable
to me about your career, Mario --

00:35:50.570 --> 00:35:53.550
and it's surely remarkable
to everyone who's sitting

00:35:53.550 --> 00:35:58.190
in this audience -- is that very
fact, the breadth, the range.

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:04.600
The video gave us a notion of
that range, although it did leave

00:36:04.600 --> 00:36:07.040
out your most recent novel,
"Cinco Esquinas" because --

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:08.340
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa:
"Cinco Esquinas."

00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:10.470
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: -- we didn't know
it would publish in time for this.

00:36:10.470 --> 00:36:15.920
But your writing spans from -- as
it says, from fiction, to drama,

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:17.480
to journalistic opinion,

00:36:17.480 --> 00:36:21.540
to political commentary,
to literary criticism.

00:36:21.540 --> 00:36:26.340
And in fiction alone it
ranges from novels of ideas,

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:31.270
to picaresque novels, to
thrillers, and mysteries,

00:36:31.270 --> 00:36:36.990
and novels that are set in 20th
century history in a most kind

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:40.330
of stark and powerful way.

00:36:40.330 --> 00:36:44.430
In other words, you wear
many hats as a writer.

00:36:44.430 --> 00:36:47.640
There are many hats that you wear,
and you have learned to wear all

00:36:47.640 --> 00:36:53.310
of them in sort of an
extraordinarily, masterly fashion.

00:36:53.310 --> 00:36:58.620
Which of those hats would you
say represents the true Mario

00:36:58.620 --> 00:37:00.200
Vargas Llosa?

00:37:00.200 --> 00:37:01.500
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Oh,

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:06.580
I think all my books
represent what I am, no?

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:13.840 position:56%
Well, Borges -- Jorge Luis Borges,
said something that I think is very,

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:19.010
very real, that when
you look yourself

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:23.930
at the mirror you don't
know how is your face.

00:37:23.930 --> 00:37:30.100
Others know immediately and
say, "Well, you are awful.

00:37:30.100 --> 00:37:32.710
You are very handsome."

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:35.240
But you don't know.

00:37:35.240 --> 00:37:39.680
And I think that is what happens,
at least to me, with my books.

00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:44.110
I don't know the real
value of my books.

00:37:44.110 --> 00:37:46.670
I work very hard.

00:37:46.670 --> 00:37:52.470
I enjoy. I suffer sometimes
writing these books.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:56.760
But I never know exactly
what I have achieved,

00:37:56.760 --> 00:37:59.710
you know, with these books.

00:37:59.710 --> 00:38:06.210
Even when a book has some
success and receives good reviews,

00:38:06.210 --> 00:38:12.810
you are never sure if this is
exactly what the book represents,

00:38:12.810 --> 00:38:17.590
because you know that the
only way would be to wait,

00:38:17.590 --> 00:38:26.790
to wait if this book, these books
are able to transcend the proof

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:31.060
of time, which I think is
what definitely decides

00:38:31.060 --> 00:38:35.740
if what you have done is
worthwhile or not, no?

00:38:35.740 --> 00:38:39.050 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: There's also some --
a phenomenon that happens, I think,

00:38:39.050 --> 00:38:41.740
when you release a book into
the world, is there not,

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:46.580
that you have actually no concept
of how it will be received?

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:49.270
And people will receive it
in very many different ways.

00:38:49.270 --> 00:38:50.570
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Very
different ways, of course.

00:38:50.570 --> 00:38:51.900
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: And you
hear about this, then,

00:38:51.900 --> 00:38:53.960
from them, from the audience.

00:38:53.960 --> 00:38:56.960
How has that experience
been for you?

00:38:56.960 --> 00:39:02.150
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Well, what
has happened to me several times is

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:09.840
that the book may be successful
or not, but in general the way

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:17.390
in which the book is received
is very surprising, but in many,

00:39:17.390 --> 00:39:24.020
many cases the idea that I had
of the book doesn't coincide

00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:30.900
with the way in which the book was
received by critics or by the --

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:33.720
by just readers, you know.

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:39.010
And I suppose the reason is
because, the example of Borges

00:39:39.010 --> 00:39:43.420
and the mirror is that you don't
really know exactly what you have

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:47.620
achieved when you write a book.

00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:49.160
You would like to be successful.

00:39:49.160 --> 00:39:55.060
You would like this book to justify
all the time that you have invested

00:39:55.060 --> 00:39:59.760
and the energy that you
have invested in writing it,

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:02.400
but actually you never know.

00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:07.990 position:56%
And this is the great enigma, I
think, that all writers have respect

00:40:07.990 --> 00:40:09.950
of his -- their own work.

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:11.770
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Absolutely,
absolutely.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:17.720
You have thought deeply,
Mario, about power.

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:20.530
And here you are in the
heart of Washington,

00:40:20.530 --> 00:40:24.000
which represents political
power, at least in this country.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:27.390
And this is something that,
judging by your works,

00:40:27.390 --> 00:40:32.870
whether they be serious, or funny,
or whether they be large-scale

00:40:32.870 --> 00:40:37.430
or intimate, or whether they
even be historical or set

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:41.260
in the modern day, concerns you.

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:42.560
Power concerns you.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:45.590
That concern was present
in "The Green House."

00:40:45.590 --> 00:40:49.610
It was present in "Conversation
in the Cathedral," to be sure.

00:40:49.610 --> 00:40:52.020
Present in "Feast of the
Goat," "War of the Worlds."

00:40:52.020 --> 00:40:56.980
We can go right through it, and it
is really in very special evidence,

00:40:56.980 --> 00:41:02.110
I think, in your most recent
novel, "Cinco Esquinas."

00:41:02.110 --> 00:41:07.320
What is it that draws you to power?

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:09.370
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Well,
I think that literature

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:24.510
in general is something that
represents a kind of counter-power.

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:34.340
It's something that the
authors not necessarily know.

00:41:34.340 --> 00:41:42.900
But I think every good book,
a good novel, a good play,

00:41:42.900 --> 00:41:49.780
a good poem is something
that defends us readers

00:41:49.780 --> 00:41:57.730
against the potential danger that
there is in all kind of power.

00:41:57.730 --> 00:42:08.250
I think the power is something
that potentially represents a kind

00:42:08.250 --> 00:42:15.270
of danger for things like
freedom, human rights,

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:22.650
the basic rights of the individual.

00:42:22.650 --> 00:42:26.750 position:56%
And we are not always aware of this.

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:33.170
And I think there is nothing
like literature to make you aware

00:42:33.170 --> 00:42:38.560
of the dangers that the
different kind of powers

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:42.950
that are around us represent.

00:42:42.950 --> 00:42:50.530
And I think that is the most
important social function

00:42:50.530 --> 00:42:57.630
of literature, to develop in
us a kind of critical attitude,

00:42:57.630 --> 00:43:05.220
to critical spirit,
particularly vis-à-vis the powers

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:12.240 position:56%
that organize society and establish,
you know, the institutions

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:18.460
that rule, you know,
the life in society.

00:43:18.460 --> 00:43:22.420
For that reason, I think
literature is extremely important,

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:26.880
not only because the pleasure
that we receive from books,

00:43:26.880 --> 00:43:31.420
from achievements and
books of literature,

00:43:31.420 --> 00:43:38.040
but also because literature
develops in us a kind of [speaking

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:41.340
in foreign language] --
how would you say this,

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:43.260
[speaking in foreign
language] -- suspicious?

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:44.560
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah, yeah.

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:47.160
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Suspicious
about the work as it is, you know.

00:43:47.160 --> 00:43:55.250
That is the reason why all
the ideologies or systems

00:43:56.330 --> 00:44:06.220
that have pretended to control
life entirely are very suspicious

00:44:06.220 --> 00:44:12.620
of literature and establish
systems of censorship or control,

00:44:12.620 --> 00:44:17.480
because they feel,
and I think rightly,

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:25.770
that in literature they have a
kind of enemy of this appetite

00:44:25.770 --> 00:44:30.300
to control everything
and to organize life

00:44:30.300 --> 00:44:34.980
in such a determined way.

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:42.150
I think in a free country,
in a country with laws

00:44:42.150 --> 00:44:45.390
that protect the citizens,

00:44:45.390 --> 00:44:50.860
this function of literature
is not perceived.

00:44:50.860 --> 00:44:57.240
But in any country in which
freedom has started to shrink,

00:44:57.240 --> 00:45:04.580 position:56%
I think literature immediately shows
itself as something that is there

00:45:04.580 --> 00:45:09.980
to defend, you know,
these basic human rights

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:16.580
and to defend the citizens
against the excessive powers

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:22.690
that can reduce our freedom and can
even transgress our human rights.

00:45:22.690 --> 00:45:26.010
And I think this aspect of
literature is extremely,

00:45:26.010 --> 00:45:28.120
extremely important if we want

00:45:28.120 --> 00:45:32.860
to have free societies,
democratic countries.

00:45:32.860 --> 00:45:36.060
Literature is extremely
important also

00:45:36.060 --> 00:45:40.220
in this civic and political sense.

00:45:40.220 --> 00:45:49.890
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: That's a
wonderful way to put it, yes.

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:51.190
[ Applause ]

00:45:51.190 --> 00:45:55.570
I wonder to what extent you were
sensitized to the whole notion

00:45:55.570 --> 00:46:01.660
of power in your experience in the
military school, Leoncio Prado?

00:46:01.660 --> 00:46:11.720 position:56%
Was there a sense then that there
was a kind of ominous power at work?

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:13.020
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: Well, I --

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:18.480
you know, Marie, I
discovered authoritarianism

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:21.570
when I met my father
for the first time.

00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:25.230
I was 11 years old.

00:46:25.230 --> 00:46:29.100
Until then parents were divorced.

00:46:29.100 --> 00:46:33.090
And as my maternal
family was very Catholic,

00:46:33.090 --> 00:46:35.870
they were ashamed of this divorce.

00:46:35.870 --> 00:46:40.010
And so he told me that my
father was dead, you know.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:46.260
And one day suddenly when I was
11 years old, my mother told me,

00:46:46.260 --> 00:46:49.300
"You know that your
father is alive, no?"

00:46:49.300 --> 00:46:52.740
And I think I haven't yet
recovered, you know [laughter].

00:46:52.740 --> 00:46:57.040
From the impression that I
had when my mother told me

00:46:57.040 --> 00:46:59.040
that my father was alive.

00:46:59.040 --> 00:47:06.550
So I said -- I asked to her, "And
when I'm going to meet my father?"

00:47:06.550 --> 00:47:08.170
And she told me, "Right away.

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:09.590
Immediately."

00:47:09.590 --> 00:47:11.940 position:56%
We go to the hotel, and he is there.

00:47:11.940 --> 00:47:14.330
And I went to live with my father.

00:47:14.330 --> 00:47:17.870
My father reconciled and
-- my parents reconciled.

00:47:17.870 --> 00:47:21.730
And with my father I
discovered authoritarianism.

00:47:21.730 --> 00:47:25.130
He was a very authoritarian
personality.

00:47:25.130 --> 00:47:33.080
And I remember very well how
my life changed completely

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:35.600 position:56%
since I went to live with my father.

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:40.150
I discovered things that I didn't
know that they exist, you know.

00:47:40.150 --> 00:47:42.020
Fear, for example.

00:47:42.020 --> 00:47:46.420
I had such a fear with
this strange man,

00:47:46.420 --> 00:47:50.280
because he was completely
strange in my life.

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:55.330 position:56%
And I think that the military school
was just a continuation of the kind

00:47:55.330 --> 00:48:01.540
of authoritarianism that I had
at home because of my father.

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:07.160
And I think the -- probably it was
there, during those early years

00:48:07.160 --> 00:48:14.560
of my adolescence, you know, that
I started to hate dictatorships,

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:16.820
any kind of dictatorship.

00:48:16.820 --> 00:48:23.920
And this, I think, has been
something recurrent in my life,

00:48:23.920 --> 00:48:33.280
in my writings, and the way in
which some authorities exercise

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:39.690
with brutality, with abuse,
without respecting, you know,

00:48:39.690 --> 00:48:48.310
the most elementary forms in life
is something that I cannot resist.

00:48:48.310 --> 00:48:56.140
And I think this explains,
probably, why in so many books,

00:48:56.140 --> 00:49:04.320
in so many novels, the theme of
authoritarian power is central,

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:10.780 position:56%
is something that has been repeating
itself in what I have written,

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:15.830 position:56%
because in my life this is something
that has produced in me this kind

00:49:15.830 --> 00:49:24.230
of protest of rebellion, you know,
against any kind of abuse of power.

00:49:24.230 --> 00:49:26.380
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well, if you're
talking about power you --

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:28.410
and you're talking about
authoritarian power,

00:49:28.410 --> 00:49:31.070
you're also talking about
corruption eventually.

00:49:31.070 --> 00:49:35.240
And you're talking about -- also
about rebels against the power,

00:49:35.240 --> 00:49:42.270
which is what you attribute the
great work of literature doing.

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:46.370
But you've thought
deeply also about rebels.

00:49:46.370 --> 00:49:51.960
And you've -- I'm talking now about
Flora Tristan, for instance who --

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:55.720
the Peruvian grandmother
of the artist Paul Gaugin,

00:49:55.720 --> 00:50:00.360
who was a feminist revolutionary
and a character in your novel

00:50:00.360 --> 00:50:04.860
"El Paraiso en la Otra
Esquina," which was "The Way

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:06.790
to Paradise" it was in English.

00:50:06.790 --> 00:50:09.610
And I'm thinking about
also Sir Roger Casement

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:13.910
who in a way was a
rebel in his own right,

00:50:13.910 --> 00:50:16.230
the hero of "Dream of the Celt."

00:50:16.230 --> 00:50:19.930
And I'm thinking, too, about
la Retaquita, who is Julieta,

00:50:19.930 --> 00:50:23.250
the heroine of your most
recent book, "Cinco Esquinas."

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:28.490
And these were all people who
are after some kind of truth.

00:50:28.490 --> 00:50:34.190
They are trying to right
a wrong, as it were.

00:50:34.190 --> 00:50:37.810
And they're bucking a
whole system to do it.

00:50:37.810 --> 00:50:42.450
So rebels also, aside from power,
are very much a theme in your work.

00:50:42.450 --> 00:50:43.830
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa:
Oh, without a doubt.

00:50:43.830 --> 00:50:48.990
I -- these kind of
characters I admire very much.

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:54.290
I mean, people who are not --

00:50:54.290 --> 00:51:01.710
who don't accept the world as
it is and want to change it.

00:51:01.710 --> 00:51:12.100
Usually they want to change
it in the good way, in the --

00:51:12.100 --> 00:51:16.030
to reduce sufferances,
to reduce misery,

00:51:16.030 --> 00:51:20.770
to defend freedom against
oppression.

00:51:20.770 --> 00:51:26.810
But in certain cases there
are rebels who are --

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:31.930
who have a very wrong
idea of what they want

00:51:31.930 --> 00:51:34.050
to achieve with the rebellion.

00:51:34.050 --> 00:51:35.350
But it doesn't matter.

00:51:35.350 --> 00:51:40.570
Even if they are wrong, and
even if they fail completely

00:51:40.570 --> 00:51:45.700
in what they try to do, there is
something that I think is admirable

00:51:45.700 --> 00:51:51.090
in these people who are not
conformist and that consider

00:51:51.090 --> 00:51:57.320
that the world should change
in order to be a better place,

00:51:57.320 --> 00:52:00.260
at least for some people.

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:03.390
This kind of character
I admire very much,

00:52:03.390 --> 00:52:05.920
and I think that is the reason why

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:08.990
in my novels sometimes I
am not totally conscious

00:52:08.990 --> 00:52:10.720
of what I am doing.

00:52:10.720 --> 00:52:14.490
But in general when I have a
perspective of what I have done,

00:52:14.490 --> 00:52:19.520 position:56%
I discover that this kind of
character is recurring in my novels.

00:52:19.520 --> 00:52:22.110
Sometimes they came from history.

00:52:22.110 --> 00:52:25.260
In other cases, I invented
characters.

00:52:25.260 --> 00:52:27.530
But the attitude that
they represent,

00:52:27.530 --> 00:52:31.680
rebellion against the world
as it is, I think is something

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:37.290
that I am deeply attached.

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:45.590
And in a way I think that this
is also a consequence of my love

00:52:45.590 --> 00:52:49.600
of books and of literature
and fiction.

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:55.720
I think the books gave me
since my first readings

00:52:55.720 --> 00:53:02.680 position:56%
when I was very young this idea of
the adventure, life as an adventure.

00:53:02.680 --> 00:53:06.590
Life as an adventure to change
life for the better, no?

00:53:06.590 --> 00:53:13.560
I read Alexander Dumas, the history
of the musketeers, for example,

00:53:13.560 --> 00:53:19.480
and I remember the way in which
I enjoy and I identified myself,

00:53:19.480 --> 00:53:23.080
you know, with the musketeers,
with d'Artagnan, with Porthos,

00:53:23.080 --> 00:53:28.450
with Aramis, and afterward
when I started

00:53:28.450 --> 00:53:37.020
to read more important books,
you know, Moreau, Faulkner,

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:40.730
the kind of heroes that are
[inaudible] a kind of war

00:53:40.730 --> 00:53:44.800
with the world as it is were heroes

00:53:44.800 --> 00:53:48.120
with which I identified
myself immediately.

00:53:48.120 --> 00:53:52.790
So it's not strange that
I have tried in my novels

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:54.280 position:56%
to produce these kind of characters.

00:53:54.280 --> 00:53:55.770
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: To adopt
the adventure, yes.

00:53:55.770 --> 00:53:57.600
And you do -- and you do, indeed.

00:53:57.600 --> 00:53:59.100
For whom do you write, Mario?

00:53:59.100 --> 00:54:03.570 position:56%
For whom -- who is -- what you write
your fiction or your nonfiction,

00:54:03.570 --> 00:54:05.250
do you have someone in mind?

00:54:05.250 --> 00:54:06.550
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: No.

00:54:06.550 --> 00:54:07.850
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Who is that person?

00:54:07.850 --> 00:54:10.810
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: I don't
think I am thinking in a reader --

00:54:10.810 --> 00:54:15.690
in a particular kind of reader
when I am writing a novel.

00:54:15.690 --> 00:54:21.310
No, for me, to write a novel is
something, I repeat, very solitary.

00:54:21.310 --> 00:54:28.780
I secluded myself in a world
which came from memories,

00:54:28.780 --> 00:54:34.620
images from the memory
which produce inventions,

00:54:34.620 --> 00:54:38.010
which produce another
images, which are invented.

00:54:38.010 --> 00:54:43.160
But the point of departure is
something -- it's always memory.

00:54:43.160 --> 00:54:48.070
It's images that are
preserved in the memory.

00:54:48.070 --> 00:54:53.700
Images that were produced by
experiences, by living experiences,

00:54:53.700 --> 00:54:56.660
and then are always
the point of departure

00:54:56.660 --> 00:54:59.270
for the imagination, for invention.

00:54:59.270 --> 00:55:04.160
But I don't think I have a
particular kind of reader

00:55:04.160 --> 00:55:07.230
in which I am thinking
when I am writing, no.

00:55:07.230 --> 00:55:08.950
What I try to do, of course --

00:55:08.950 --> 00:55:12.420
and I think this is something
that many writers try to do

00:55:12.420 --> 00:55:19.510
when they are writing -- I try
to divide myself in the reader

00:55:19.510 --> 00:55:28.710 position:56%
that is reading what I am writing to
see if the techniques are effective

00:55:28.710 --> 00:55:35.530
and can really persuade the
reader of what they say.

00:55:35.530 --> 00:55:39.900
But I think this is a very
personal kind of reader,

00:55:39.900 --> 00:55:45.620
and I don't think I have a
particular audience in mind

00:55:45.620 --> 00:55:48.260
when I am writing a book.

00:55:48.260 --> 00:55:53.700
It's different when I write an
article or I write an essay.

00:55:53.700 --> 00:55:58.640
That is different, because that
you try to reach a kind of public.

00:55:58.640 --> 00:56:00.480
But this is not the case
when I write fiction --

00:56:00.480 --> 00:56:01.780
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: When
you write fiction.

00:56:01.780 --> 00:56:03.080
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa: -- at all.

00:56:03.080 --> 00:56:04.380
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yes, I understand.

00:56:04.380 --> 00:56:09.430
Now you are, as we all
know from just listening

00:56:09.430 --> 00:56:14.110
to the Ambassadors here who -- or
the list of names who have come

00:56:14.110 --> 00:56:16.460
to pay you tribute
and to hear you --

00:56:16.460 --> 00:56:17.990
that you're a citizen of the world.

00:56:17.990 --> 00:56:23.500
You have -- you're Peruvian,
but you live in Spain.

00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:25.490
You hold Spanish citizenship.

00:56:25.490 --> 00:56:27.660
You have lived in Britain.

00:56:27.660 --> 00:56:28.960
You've lived in France.

00:56:28.960 --> 00:56:32.530
And you are read and
loved the world over.

00:56:32.530 --> 00:56:35.010
I can't even count the
number of languages

00:56:35.010 --> 00:56:36.890
that you're translated into.

00:56:36.890 --> 00:56:42.280
So my question to you is do
you think of yourself in terms

00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:49.290
of allegiance to any kind of
nationality, any kind of culture?

00:56:49.290 --> 00:56:51.200
Where are your allegiances?

00:56:51.200 --> 00:56:54.010
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa:
Well, as you said,

00:56:54.010 --> 00:56:58.930
I think I have become
a citizen of the world.

00:56:58.930 --> 00:57:01.060
The -- particularly the world

00:57:01.060 --> 00:57:09.570
in which we live now permits
this kind of world citizenship.

00:57:09.570 --> 00:57:16.510
But I think for a writer
that our basic experiences,

00:57:16.510 --> 00:57:25.470
which are the major source of
his fantasy, or when he writes.

00:57:25.470 --> 00:57:30.690
And I think in my case,
these basic experiences,

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:36.210
I had it when I was young,
when I was an adolescent,

00:57:36.210 --> 00:57:43.520 position:56%
and probably that is the reason
why, in spite of living outside Peru

00:57:43.520 --> 00:57:48.730
so many, many years, I am
always returning directly

00:57:48.730 --> 00:57:54.820
or undirectly [sic] to Peruvian
themes, to Peruvian environments,

00:57:54.820 --> 00:58:01.110
to Peruvian geography, and to
Peruvian language, you know,

00:58:01.110 --> 00:58:04.370
the way in which we speak
the Spanish is something

00:58:04.370 --> 00:58:12.330
that is intimately linked to the
kind of Spanish that I write.

00:58:12.330 --> 00:58:17.960
And I think the reason is
because the basic experiences

00:58:17.960 --> 00:58:22.310
that form my personality
were experiences that I had

00:58:22.310 --> 00:58:24.390
in Peru when I was young, no?

00:58:24.390 --> 00:58:28.660
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: There -- I think
it was Garcia Marquez who said,

00:58:28.660 --> 00:58:34.770
"The writer that I became was a
fully-formed mind, in a sense,

00:58:34.770 --> 00:58:39.720
or heart," by the time
he was eight years old.

00:58:39.720 --> 00:58:44.470
The idea that you -- your --
those first experiences --

00:58:44.470 --> 00:58:47.250 position:56%
and for you it was in -- you were in
Bolivia, and then you were in Piura.

00:58:47.250 --> 00:58:49.670
You were moving around as a child.

00:58:49.670 --> 00:58:55.650
So you have this natural, for as
long as you can remember perhaps,

00:58:55.650 --> 00:59:00.370
a kind of fluid relationship
to the world, would you say?

00:59:00.370 --> 00:59:01.670
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa:
Yes, that is true.

00:59:01.670 --> 00:59:09.880 position:56%
And on the other hand, I feel the
basic experiences were not literary.

00:59:09.880 --> 00:59:16.520
My literary experiences are
much less universal, you know.

00:59:16.520 --> 00:59:24.620
I -- for example, I remember
the way in which I was impressed

00:59:24.620 --> 00:59:31.180
when I was -- I don't know --
12, 13 years old watching a play

00:59:31.180 --> 00:59:35.860
by Arthur Miller, "Muerte de un
Viajante," "Death of a Salesman."

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:37.160
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Salesman.

00:59:37.160 --> 00:59:39.800
&gt;&gt; Mario Vargas Llosa:
And I was so impressed

00:59:39.800 --> 00:59:47.550 position:56%
because it was the first play which,
like a modern novel, could change,

00:59:47.550 --> 00:59:52.530
you know, time, spaces,
