something very different of the kind

01:00:23.300 --> 01:00:27.570
of realism that was at that
time in Latin America popular.

01:00:27.570 --> 01:00:34.320
Not a realism that was negligible
with form, with aestheticism.

01:00:34.320 --> 01:00:35.690
No, the contrary.

01:00:35.690 --> 01:00:46.760 position:56%
Flaubert could match realism and the
research of beauty, of perfection,

01:00:46.760 --> 01:00:54.030
the kind in which he wore
the language to reach the --

01:00:54.030 --> 01:00:56.610
les mots justes, the right word.

01:00:56.610 --> 01:01:03.140
You know? Was such that could match
perfect realism and aestheticism.

01:01:03.140 --> 01:01:10.270
And so, I think I owe
enormously to foreign writers,

01:01:10.270 --> 01:01:14.940
not only Latin American writers.

01:01:14.940 --> 01:01:17.920
It was the case of
Faulkner, for example.

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:23.580 position:56%
I remember when I read the first
novels by Faulkner, I was entranced.

01:01:23.580 --> 01:01:29.800
I discovered that the novel could
be so rich if you use, you know,

01:01:29.800 --> 01:01:34.880
all these techniques
that Faulkner was using

01:01:34.880 --> 01:01:40.380
with such easiness in his novels.

01:01:40.380 --> 01:01:46.020
I remember how important it was for
me to read, for example, Malraux,

01:01:46.020 --> 01:01:56.310
the way in which Malraux described
masses of people moving, acting.

01:01:56.310 --> 01:01:59.630
It was really extraordinary and --

01:01:59.630 --> 01:02:06.560 position:56%
so my literary training is much more
universal, is not Latin American.

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:11.440 position:56%
No. But the basic experiences, yes,
